# Agent Context (CLAUDE.md) - Python stack

> This repo applies the [Excellence Standards - Engineering (ESE)](.standards/STANDARDS.md). These instructions apply to any AI coding agent working in this repository.

## Bootstrap

Run the bootstrap script before any other work if this project has unfilled ESE placeholders. See the canonical AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md for the full bootstrap check and procedure.

## Stack-specific commands

**Test runner.** This project uses `pytest` (replace with `unittest` / `nose2` / etc. if different). Before declaring a feature complete, run:

```
pytest
```

For a tighter loop during development:

```
pytest -x -q <specific-test-file>
```

**Lint.** This project uses `ruff` (replace with `flake8` / `pylint` / etc. if different):

```
ruff check .
ruff format --check .
```

**Type check.** This project uses `mypy` (replace with `pyright` / `pyre` if different):

```
mypy .
```

**Build / package.** If this project publishes a package:

```
python -m build
```

**Pre-commit.** Install the hook once per clone:

```
ln -sf ../../scripts/pre-commit .git/hooks/pre-commit
```

The ESE pre-commit hook runs `scripts/verify.sh` which invokes the full linter suite.

## Python-specific ESE notes

- Follow PEP 8 conventions; `ruff` enforces.
- Type hints required on all public functions per ESE §5 code-quality requirements.
- `pyproject.toml` is the canonical build manifest; no `setup.py` unless there's a specific reason.
- Dependency pinning via `poetry.lock` / `pip-tools`-generated `requirements.txt` / `uv.lock`; choose one and be explicit.
- Vulnerability scan via `pip-audit` or `safety check`; run in CI.
- Secrets must not land in source; use `python-dotenv` for `.env` with `.env.example` checked in.

## Universal ESE rules

The full set of ESE rules that apply to every project (artifact scaffolding, writing standards, commit discipline, release discipline, submodule upgrades) live in the canonical [AGENTS.md](.standards/starters/AGENTS.md) at `.standards/starters/AGENTS.md`. Read that file for cross-stack rules. This CLAUDE.md supplements it with Python-specific commands.
